{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585137"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:03:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:03:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14901"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14901"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0,0.71,0.01,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82079"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7592"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14901"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67286"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7870"},{"type":"tags","id":"8108"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27962"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82079"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute phase proteins are important mediators of the inflammatory response. They are rapidly produced during infection or tissue injury and help coordinate the body\u0027s defence mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organs is the primary site of acute phase protein production?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bone marrow","Gallbladder","Liver","Pancreas","Spleen"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary site of acute phase protein production. Hepatocytes synthesise these proteins in response to inflammatory cytokines, particularly interleukin-6, interleukin-1, and tumour necrosis factor alpha.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile the \u003Cstrong\u003Espleen\u003C/strong\u003E is important in immune function, it does not produce acute phase proteins. The \u003Cstrong\u003Egallbladder\u003C/strong\u003E stores and concentrates bile but has no protein synthesis role. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreas\u003C/strong\u003E produces digestive enzymes and hormones but not acute phase proteins. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E produces blood cells but is not involved in acute phase protein synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon acute phase proteins include C-reactive protein, serum amyloid A, fibrinogen, and complement factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute phase proteins are primarily synthesised by hepatocytes in the liver as part of the acute phase response","Common acute phase proteins include C-reactive protein, serum amyloid A, and fibrinogen"],"references":["Tigner A, Ibrahim SA, Murray IV. Histology, White Blood Cell. [Updated 2022 Nov 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563148/","Playfair, J. H. L., \u0026 Chain, B. M. (2012). Immunology at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Jain S, Gautam V, Naseem S. Acute-phase proteins: As diagnostic tool. J Pharm Bioallied Sci. 2011 Jan;3(1):118-27. doi: 10.4103/0975-7406.76489. PMID: 21430962; PMCID: PMC3053509."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67286"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14901"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"